{"title_page": "I Hope (Gabby Barrett song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Hope\n| cover      = GabbyBarrettIHope.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gabby Barrett]]\n| album      = \n| released   = July 29, 2019\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=29}}\n| label      = [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Gabby Barrett|Zachary Kale|[[Jon Nite]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Ross Copperman]]}}\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\"'''I Hope'''\" is a song co-written and recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Gabby Barrett]]. She released the single independently following her third-place finish on [[American Idol (season 16)|season 16]] of ''[[American Idol]]''. It led to her signing a deal with [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]], and it was released as her debut single in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicrow.com/2019/06/warner-music-nashville-signs-gabby-barrett/|title=Warner Music Nashville Signs Gabby Barrett|date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nGabby Barrett co-wrote \"I Hope\" with Zachary Kale and [[Jon Nite]], and the track was produced by [[Ross Copperman]].<ref name=roland>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8527742/gabby-barrett-i-hope-making-of |title=Makin' Tracks: 'Idol' Alum Gabby Barrett's 'I Hope' Is Not What the Title Implies|date=August 19, 2019 |first= Tom|last= Roland |work=Billboard }}</ref> They originally sat down to write a song about a woman suffering a breakup and still wishing for her ex to be happy, but Barrett decided to turn it toward a more revengeful nature: \"The fact is that sometimes we hope for the worst when it comes to our exes. We would never voice that, but it wreaks [havoc] inside. This song now says the things that maybe you or I never said.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/gabby-barrett-new-song-i-hope-american-idol/|title=American Idol Alum Gabby Barrett Turns Up the Revenge on Vengeful New Song 'I Hope'|author=Tricia Despres|date=May 23, 2019|work=|publisher=People.com|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"I Hope\" was filmed in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and premiered on February 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nashville.com/rising-star-gabby-barrett-releases-i-hope-video/|title=Rising Star Gabby Barrett Releases \u201cI Hope\u201d Video|author=Jerry Holthouse|date=February 7, 2019|work=|publisher=Nashville.com|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nBarrett returned to the ''American Idol'' stage to give her first televised performance of \"I Hope\" on May 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc.com/shows/american-idol/video/vdka9710510|title=Gabby Barrett Performs Her New Song 'I Hope' Live on American Idol|author=|date=May 5, 2019|work=|publisher=|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"I Hope\" debuted at number 74 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for the chart dated January 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artist=Gabby+Barrett&chart_name=Hot+100|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"I Hope\" was certified Gold by the RIAA for half a million units in sales and streams on January 16, 2020.{{Certification Cite Ref |region=United States|title=I Hope |artist=Gabby Barrett |type=single }} The song has sold 167,000 copies in the United States as of March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |title=Top 30 Digital Country Singles Sales Chart: March 2, 2020|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44155-top-30-digital-country-singles-sales-chart-march-2-2020|work=Rough Stock |date=March 4, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada ([[Canadian Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Gabby+Barrett&chartcode=CAN|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Billboard Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 56\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada Country (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Gabby+Barrett&chartcode=CCW|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Canada Country|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Gabby+Barrett&chartcode=HSI|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Country Airplay]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-airplay/2020-04-18|title=Billboard Country Airplay|work=Billboard|date=April 18, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Hot Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-songs/2020-04-11|title=Hot Country Songs|work=Billboard|date=April 11, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-02-07/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 18, 2020}}</ref> \n| 53\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Chart (2019)\n! Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Hot Country Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2019/hot-country-songs|title=Hot Country Songs \u2013 Year-End 2019|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n| 73\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Version\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\"| Various\n| January 25, 2019\n| {{hlist|Digital download}}\n| Original\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| July 29, 2019\n| {{hlist|[[Country radio]]}}\n| Original\n| [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]\n|-\n| April 17, 2020\n| {{hlist|Digital download}}\n| Remix feat. [[Charlie Puth]]\n| [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]  \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 singles]]\n[[Category:2019 debut singles]]\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:Gabby Barrett songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records Nashville singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gabby Barrett]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jon Nite]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Ross Copperman]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Hope\n| cover      = GabbyBarrettIHope.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gabby Barrett]]\n| album      = \n| released   = July 29, 2019\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=29}}\n| label      = [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Gabby Barrett|Zachary Kale|[[Jon Nite]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Ross Copperman]]}}\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\"'''I Hope'''\" is a song co-written and recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Gabby Barrett]]. She released the single independently following her third-place finish on [[American Idol (season 16)|season 16]] of ''[[American Idol]]''. It led to her signing a deal with [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]], and it was released as her debut single in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicrow.com/2019/06/warner-music-nashville-signs-gabby-barrett/|title=Warner Music Nashville Signs Gabby Barrett|date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\nGabby Barrett co-wrote \"I Hope\" with Zachary Kale and [[Jon Nite]], and the track was produced by [[Ross Copperman]].<ref name=roland>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8527742/gabby-barrett-i-hope-making-of |title=Makin' Tracks: 'Idol' Alum Gabby Barrett's 'I Hope' Is Not What the Title Implies|date=August 19, 2019 |first= Tom|last= Roland |work=Billboard }}</ref> They originally sat down to write a song about a woman suffering a breakup and still wishing for her ex to be happy, but Barrett decided to turn it toward a more revengeful nature: \"The fact is that sometimes we hope for the worst when it comes to our exes. We would never voice that, but it wreaks [havoc] inside. This song now says the things that maybe you or I never said.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/country/gabby-barrett-new-song-i-hope-american-idol/|title=American Idol Alum Gabby Barrett Turns Up the Revenge on Vengeful New Song 'I Hope'|author=Tricia Despres|date=May 23, 2019|work=|publisher=People.com|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"I Hope\" was filmed in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and premiered on February 7, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nashville.com/rising-star-gabby-barrett-releases-i-hope-video/|title=Rising Star Gabby Barrett Releases \u201cI Hope\u201d Video|author=Jerry Holthouse|date=February 7, 2019|work=|publisher=Nashville.com|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nBarrett returned to the ''American Idol'' stage to give her first televised performance of \"I Hope\" on May 5, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc.com/shows/american-idol/video/vdka9710510|title=Gabby Barrett Performs Her New Song 'I Hope' Live on American Idol|author=|date=May 5, 2019|work=|publisher=|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"I Hope\" debuted at number 74 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for the chart dated January 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artist=Gabby+Barrett&chart_name=Hot+100|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"I Hope\" was certified Gold by the RIAA for half a million units in sales and streams on January 16, 2020.{{Certification Cite Ref |region=United States|title=I Hope |artist=Gabby Barrett |type=single }} The song has sold 167,000 copies in the United States as of March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |title=Top 30 Digital Country Singles Sales Chart: March 2, 2020|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/03/44155-top-30-digital-country-singles-sales-chart-march-2-2020|work=Rough Stock |date=March 4, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada ([[Canadian Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Gabby+Barrett&chartcode=CAN|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Billboard Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 56\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada Country (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Gabby+Barrett&chartcode=CCW|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Canada Country|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Gabby+Barrett&chartcode=HSI|title=Chart Search: Gabby Barrett, Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Country Airplay]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://