{"title_page": "White-bibbed manakin", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = White-bibbed manakin\n| image = PipraLeucorrhoaWolf.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701099/0 |title=''Corapipo leucorrhoa'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Corapipo\n| species = leucorrhoa\n| authority = ([[Philip Sclater|Sclater]], 1863)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''white-bibbed manakin''' (''Corapipo leucorrhoa'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Pipridae]].\nIt is found in [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]] and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]].\n\n''Corapipo leucorrhoa'' previously included [[white-ruffed manakin]] (''[[Corapipo altera]]'') which has been split into a separate species.  When they were a single species ''Corapipo leucorrhoa'' was called white-ruffed manakin.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1307485}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:manakin, white-bibbed}}\n[[Category:Corapipo|white-bibbed manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Venezuelan Andes]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1863|white-bibbed manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = White-bibbed manakin\n| image = PipraLeucorrhoaWolf.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701099/0 |title=''Corapipo leucorrhoa'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Corapipo\n| species = leucorrhoa\n| authority = ([[Philip Sclater|Sclater]], 1863)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''white-bibbed manakin''' (''Corapipo leucorrhoa'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Pipridae]] family.\nIt is found in [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]]s.\n\n''Corapipo leucorrhoa'' previously included [[white-ruffed manakin]] (''[[Corapipo altera]]'') which has been split into a separate species.  When they were a single species ''Corapipo leucorrhoa'' was called white-ruffed manakin.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1307485}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:manakin, white-bibbed}}\n[[Category:Corapipo|white-bibbed manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Venezuelan Andes]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1863|white-bibbed manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White-bibbed_manakin"}
{"title_page": "Sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin\n| image = \n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701178/0 |title=''Neopelma sulphureiventer'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Neopelma\n| species = sulphureiventer\n| authority = ([[Carl Eduard Hellmayr|Hellmayr]], 1903)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin''' (''Neopelma sulphureiventer''), or '''sulphur-bellied neopelma''', is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Pipridae]].  It is found in the western [[Amazon Basin]] of [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]] and [[Peru]].  Its natural [[habitat]] is [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1302825}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:tyrant-manakin, sulphur-bellied}}\n[[Category:Neopelma|sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Amazon Basin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Peruvian Amazon]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Bolivian Amazon]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1903|sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Eduard Hellmayr|sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin\n| image = \n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701178/0 |title=''Neopelma sulphureiventer'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Neopelma\n| species = sulphureiventer\n| authority = ([[Carl Eduard Hellmayr|Hellmayr]], 1903)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin''' (''Neopelma sulphureiventer''), or '''sulphur-bellied neopelma''', is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Pipridae]] family.  It is found in the western [[Amazon Basin]] of [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]] and [[Peru]].  Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1302825}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:tyrant-manakin, sulphur-bellied}}\n[[Category:Neopelma|sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Amazon Basin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Peruvian Amazon]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Bolivian Amazon]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1903|sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Eduard Hellmayr|sulphur-bellied tyrant-manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulphur-bellied_tyrant-manakin"}
{"title_page": "Dragon's Mouth (play)", "text_new": "{{Infobox play\n| name              = Dragon's Mouth \n| image             = File:Dragon's Mouth (play).jpg\n| image_size        =\n| caption           =\n| writer            = [[J.B. Priestley]] <br> [[Jacquetta Hawkes]]\n| setting           = \n| date of premiere  = 13 April 1952\n| original language = English\n| place             =[[Malvern Festival (1929\u201339)|Malvern Festival]]\n| series            = \n| subject           = \n| genre             = Drama\n}}\n'''''Dragon's Mouth''''' is a 1952 play by [[J.B. Priestley]] and his wife [[Jacquetta Hawkes]]. It features four characters on a [[yacht]] trapped in [[quarantine]] off the [[West Indies]], discussing life.\n\nIt premiered at the [[The Malvern Festival (1929-1939)|Malvern Festival]] before transferring to the [[Gillian Lynne Theatre|Winter Garden Theatre]] in [[London]]'s [[West End theatre|West End]], running for 55 performances. It starred [[Rosamund John]], [[Dulcie Gray]], [[Michael Denison]] and [[Norman Wooland]].<ref>Wearing p.162-63</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Wearing, J.P. ''The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel''.  Rowman & Littlefield, 2014.\n\n{{JBPriestley}}\n\n[[Category:1952 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by J. B. Priestley]]\n[[Category:British plays]]\n[[Category:West End plays]]\n\n{{1950s-play-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox play\n| name              = Dragon's Mouth \n| image             = File:Dragon's Mouth (play).jpg\n| image_size        =\n| caption           =\n| writer            = [[J.B. Priestley]] <br> [[Jacquetta Hawkes]]\n| setting           = \n| date of premiere  = 13 April 1952\n| original language = English\n| place             =[[Malvern Festival (1929\u201339)|Malvern Festival]]\n| series            = \n| subject           = \n| genre             = Drama\n}}\n'''''Dragon's Mouth''''' is a 1952 play by [[J.B. Priestley]] and his wife [[Jacquetta Hawkes]]. It features four characters on a [[yacht]] trapped in [[quarantine]] off the [[West Indies]], discussing life.\n\nIt premiered at the [[Malvern Festival]] before transferring to the [[Gillian Lynne Theatre|Winter Garden Theatre]] in [[London]]'s [[West End theatre|West End]], running for 55 performances. It starred [[Rosamund John]], [[Dulcie Gray]], [[Michael Denison]] and [[Norman Wooland]].<ref>Wearing p.162-63</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Wearing, J.P. ''The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel''.  Rowman & Littlefield, 2014.\n\n{{JBPriestley}}\n\n[[Category:1952 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by J. B. Priestley]]\n[[Category:British plays]]\n[[Category:West End plays]]\n\n{{1950s-play-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMalvern Festival(link changed toThe Malvern Festival (1929-1939)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon%27s_Mouth_(play)"}
